Analyzing Possesion Through Network Analysis

This network analysis is a visualization of all of the possessive nouns/pronouns and the nouns associated with them used throughout Nelson's entire "City Slave Girls" series. In the underlying markup, we tagged the entire phrase with a '<phr>' element. The possessive noun/pronoun was wrapped in a '<w>' element with the attribute '@type=poss'. If the adjective represents an archetype, it was given the attribute '@ana' equal to the correlating archetype from our site index. The noun was wrapped in a '<w>' element and given the attribute '@type=noun'. If the noun represents an archetype that was directly possessed, it was given an '@ana' equal to the correlating archetype from our site index. If the noun was an indirect reference to an archetype, an additional attribute, '@subtype=refTo', was added.

In the visualization, the size of the node is dependent on the out-degree, or the number of nouns that word possessed. The larger the node, the more nouns the word possessed. This is a directional graph, meaning that certain words own others; this is represented with arrows along the lines connecting the nodes. The color of the node is dependent on the in-degree, or the number of words by which the node was possessed. The more light blue a node is, the more it is being possessed by other words. The shape of the node determines if the node ever possesses another node: diamond nodes possess other nodes, and circle nodes never possess other nodes. The color of the border is dependent on different factors: black-border nodes are never owned, red-border nodes are site-index nouns or attributes that are directly possessed, orange-border nodes are site-index nouns or archetypes that are indirectly possessed, and yellow-border nodes never possess other nodes. The edge color is dependent on the article in which a link between nodes was first made (each article has a different color associated with it). Self-loops have been eliminated, and edges have been bundled.

To view a network analysis graph for an individual article, navigate to our Articles page and click on the Grammar Network link for the article you want to view.
